# AI Coding Instructions & Rules - Auto YouTube

## 🎯 1. Crucial Rules (Read before starting work)
- **Lazy Senior Dev (Ponytail)**: Follow the laziest, simplest, and shortest coding solution (YAGNI). Do not build for the future, only write code that works with minimal files and lines.
- **DOM Selectors Separation**: Never hardcode CSS/XPath Selectors inside Playwright automation files. Always read them from `docs/SELECTORS.md`.
- **SSE Real-time Logging**: Long-running processes (TTS, FFmpeg, Playwright runs) must stream detailed status logs to the client via Server-Sent Events (SSE).
- **Strict English Only**: All source code, configs, comments, logs, and other files (except `implementation_plan.md` artifact) MUST be written in English. No Thai text allowed.
- **Mandatory Self-Testing**: After editing or adding code, you MUST test it locally to verify there are no syntax errors or bugs. Deliver the task ONLY when it is fully working and verified.

## 🧱 2. Code Quality & Size Control
- **Max File Length**: Any source code file MUST NOT exceed 300-400 lines. Split logic into sub-modules if it exceeds the limit.
- **Max Function Length**: Keep functions under 50 lines. One function = One responsibility.
- **No Duplication (DRY)**: Do not write duplicate logic. Check existing utils or code files before writing new helpers.

## 💬 3. Token Efficiency & Communication
- **Concise Response**: Provide only the code blocks that need to be changed or added. Do not rewrite unchanged files.
- **Check Before Writing**: Before modifying project directory structure or file paths, summarize the proposed paths for approval.
